					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Gordon on general EQ stuff</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=90065" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
Why we will probably never see any vast improvements on EverQuest. A quote by Abashi<P>

<B>You are really taking what I said out-of-context, as I was speaking only to the pet/dual wield issue, and how doing the preferred fix on it would cause more problems than it solved.  Many of the other issues that you mentioned here are issues that we *choose* not to change because it doesn't fit into our vision for the game, not because such a change would be too difficult and prone to problems.</B><P>
 
 random loot and random spawn<P>
 
<B>This is something we *choose* not to do because it doesn't fit into the vision for EQ.  We want special items to be obtained by virtue of doing something special.  Those items should have a context in which they exist and from which they are acquired. Random loot drops will never happen for the best items.</B><P>
 
 and make alchemy a viable skill<P>
 
<B>Archery is viable for its intended use, it's just not generally viable as a primary means of combat.  This is as intended.</B><P>
 
 They will not fix stats<P>
 
<B>That's because they aren't broken.  Just because you don't like the way they work out doesn't mean that they are broken.  There are many people out there who believe that stats work fine.</B><P>
 
 Verant is just not willing to make radical changes to EverQuest<P>
 
<B>Why on Earth would we want to make radical sweeping changes to a vastly successful game?  *Most* people enjoy EQ.  *Most* people have played the game for a period of time in excess of what we forecasted.  Why would we risk messing all of that up to make radical changes to the game?  If we made radical changes, it wouldn't be EQ any longer.</B><P>
 
 If the time comes that you just don't seem to enjoy it any longer, move on<P>
 
<B>Here's a sound piece of advice.  We really don't expect people to play EQ forever, but we will continue to make improvements and additions to the game to keep the people that are here playing.  Certainly, if it gets to the point that playing the game is a chore, perhaps you should put it on the shelf.  I really can't fathom why people would keep playing if they hate the game.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
 

		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
