	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Okay, just a couple of questions and then comments.<BR>
<BR>
First off, define &quot;radical&quot; when it comes to changes. Does this mean there won't be &quot;2nd Editions&quot; etc when it comes to updating EQ?<BR>
<BR>
EQ is a computergame but what it is really is an online Role Playing Game. Because of this it needs to be treated more like a table-top RPG than a computer game.(ie. one you buy a book for and play at home) I assume of course that every developer there knows this. ;)<BR>
My suggestion is take a good hard look at table top stuff like AD&amp;D and Whitewolf products to see how rules expansion and upgrades are handled.<BR>
I agree that as a player if you don't like a game or its rules you should look elsewhere as there will be other games available. However, I also suggest players to make suggestions to the game developers and those developers to keep an open mind when reading said suggestions.<BR>
EQ is a great game but realistically this is its first edition with its many points of erata expanding game play... but that shouldn't be the end of it.<BR>
Just myself alone I could come up with many suggestions that I don't consider &quot;radical&quot; and easily changed. <BR>
The true game developer will take the suggestions of the players and fans and weave them into his/her world creating a true interactive RPG not just an online computer game.<BR>
<BR>
~Derek<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
